<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Assessment MathML 2.4//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_assessment_mathml_2_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="_u6_structures_functions_quiz" recommended_attempts="1" max_attempts="6"><title>Muscular Structures and Functions</title><page id="deca3cd08c2f44f3b0f7641aa5a1952d"><multiple_choice id="q10a" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ab65780b7290c4c91a96ba903a2dc9828">Skeletal muscle typically transfers its force to bones via:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="cf77bbb5acc442e490a1798c84585c9f" labels="false"><choice value="A">Tendons that are fused with the connective tissue in muscle.</choice><choice value="B">Ligaments that are fused with the connective tissue in muscle.</choice><choice value="C">Direct connection of Z discs to the periosteum.</choice><choice value="D">Direct connection of skeletal muscle to the periosteum using dystrophin.</choice></input><part id="q10a_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_levels_of_org_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="10"><feedback><p id="adf137bd8fb8c4669b2c8c4cde2b800c1">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa3f7e8845c764c10a87c43badbcc54a3">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="aec37cf3575b444e690be69edda8e1c30">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="acdd04fcc3c8f4875b6aa7c0d199541cf">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q2" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="adc34c774101447cd91ed22c26e058ff4">The different types of muscle tissue differ from each other by:</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="f73d58acf7044d3788edebaccdaf0543" labels="false"><choice value="A">Microscopic anatomy. </choice><choice value="B">Location.</choice><choice value="C">Type of control.</choice><choice value="D">Both microscopic anatomy and location.</choice><choice value="E">All of these choices are correct.</choice></input><part id="q2_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_major_function_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="aaaf5f5349b4b43f19eebef3c5687aead">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="af338bb2de925409c9b26f3c8e4f9e99e">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab40a9be3da1f4f1f9ca0a9a49029292a">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab588529aa6304d11b740482fe21e0f76">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="E" score="10"><feedback><p id="aa22f7bf986df4836a86065994f43aa2b">Correct.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q3" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="afee0e0cf60074801b481ab0ab5fbe0eb">The property of muscle that gives it the ability to stretch without damage is :</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="bbba3e94ac7f4354a360e1467d127560" labels="false"><choice value="A">Electrical excitability. </choice><choice value="B">Contractility.</choice><choice value="C">Extensibility.</choice><choice value="D">Elasticity.</choice><choice value="E">Thermogenesis.</choice></input><part id="q3_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_generate_ATP_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="adb17b384ba90467191db6b6bea1a565b">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab0cc383a233745e7a9ec069431d7002a">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="aa1345d9dcbc646828ccc09597be518b0">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="adb4fe7345eef47fdb4b9b938d82c5b5c">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="E" score="0"><feedback><p id="afc85a85dc7c0432ab723ee60f5b08cd4">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q5" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ad8810beb922e4340a981ae6f85c487f6">The outermost layer of connective tissue surrounding a skeletal muscle is the:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="ac1275116c944d3b8fe1cb9b2cd7019a" labels="false"><choice value="A">Tendon. </choice><choice value="B">Ligament.</choice><choice value="C">Endomysium.</choice><choice value="D">Epimysium.</choice><choice value="E">Perimysium.</choice></input><part id="q5_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_connective_layers_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa772c7ddaebc492b8288327bbf41dc2c">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab335d077351942059518e8a29a8df1dc">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae8e6329f1c1446cbb299bacdee7123db">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="ae1606f600afb4b2ca48996e6558bbde9">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="E" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa913169a00ce4c5697d3b8def32e9d46">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q6" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ae5951b28ca25442d8dfecf69d1b2791e">The type of tendon formed when the connective tissue elements of a skeletal muscle extend as a broad flat layer is called:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="f4afe5b9e11d464985ce84901d0b6cf6" labels="false"><choice value="A">Perimysium. </choice><choice value="B">Deep fascia.</choice><choice value="C">Fascicle.</choice><choice value="D">Aponeurosis.</choice><choice value="E">Endomysium.</choice></input><part id="q6_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_parallel_org_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="abdea002e30434ddcb2a06d769bbd3123">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab8a1b49463894590b7f9b037507b6bc7">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="aadc0cf5cb7b74283a5bb19c1b754012e">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="adf3dd387717148a9a4e3a2d148c22b21">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="E" score="0"><feedback><p id="afe5013e99c9840f0986f5627e9aae7c1">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q9" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af91d5d2d32034302a96af5d8cb963a82">The contractile organelles of a skeletal muscle fiber are thread-like structures called:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="ffdbcd7090c94f8199b4c7d9ce75f831" labels="false"><choice value="A">Myofibrils. </choice><choice value="B">Myoglobin.</choice><choice value="C">Mitochondria.</choice><choice value="D">Z discs.</choice><choice value="E">M lines.</choice></input><part id="q9_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_parallel_org_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="10"><feedback><p id="aeb482f857a6b4ff380435c03c3482621">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aeef61c0f59e348a0b36c78c342a68c40">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab3a4a88cde1949bdb7cf7b6d076a5831">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="afeb6ab9ee09145068dab6d2139633a66">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="E" score="0"><feedback><p id="abadda02ddec64fcca5efbef0c9a2ccb4">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q1_s" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ab99cf9ca08624360bde1158178cb9758">Which of the following is true concerning Muscle Tone?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e7213ea024004ee684f1623c434e18a9" labels="false"><choice value="A">It requires all muscle fibers to be contracted.</choice><choice value="B">It is not required for proper posture.</choice><choice value="C">It helps with stronger movements.</choice><choice value="D">It prevents the stabilization of joints.</choice></input><part id="q1_s_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_tone_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="af61ca8671e2044ef9368ceab8ea274cf">Incorrect. It only requires some of the muscle fibers to be contracted so the rest can relax.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="adf6653911954410c9d0e8544c95a8f34">Incorrect. It is required for proper posture.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad6e5c56bd1fd4d09bf080e5984ab06f1">Correct. Muscle tone allows for stronger movement because not all muscle fibers need to be stimulated from rest.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="abc1ff7b579af4559b433b057777ec65f">Incorrect. Muscle tone is responsible for adding stability to joints.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q4_s" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af121e77b3a4f4b2ab0cc0cd8d2b02ab6">Which of the following connects muscle to bone?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e031ee03d0f64a5f944bef10a9d08f60" labels="false"><choice value="A">Aponeuroses</choice><choice value="B">Tendons</choice><choice value="C">Ligaments</choice><choice value="D">Bursae</choice></input><part id="q4_s_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_bursae_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="af466c12e431a4cbd94794275a5a4c81f">Incorrect. Aponeuroses connect muscle to muscle.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad458d8512ffd4e6aac6f1b162174e48e">Correct. Tendons connect muscle to bone.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="afdbe038df5b04ff198b6e93a4e4797f0">Incorrect. Ligaments connect bone to bone.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="adda5012d55c04881a26e733325870a76">Incorrect. Bursae are fluid filled sacs that can reduce friction.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q5_s" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ab7ca3e11219341268a6a572fd2d6e77a">To gain speed in motion, third class levers sacrifice what?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="d4cf23bfe80b47c5b146fe7653cf24ec" labels="false"><choice value="A">Flexion</choice><choice value="B">Stability</choice><choice value="C">Extension</choice><choice value="D">Force</choice></input><part id="q5_s_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_levers_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab067d6c346f64418899148ee0e2e755a">Incorrect. Flexion is the action of pulling the head down toward the chest</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aafed3ae8aef94c34adf5ed4584017909">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac197396088c440a0a017efa973b80b6c">Incorrect. Extension is the action of pulling the head away from the chest.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="ac50e5fe322af422a91cfa0789d28342a">Correct. The force is applied between the load and the fulcrum of a third class lever which increase speed and lower the force.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q6_s" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aa49dbdffcba44e8194fdfb66f52c215d">Prime mover is another term for which of the following?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="be8c829ccff740c58bdb838ec5ed67ae" labels="false"><choice value="A">Antagonist</choice><choice value="B">Agonist</choice><choice value="C">Synergist</choice><choice value="D">Fixator</choice></input><part id="q6_s_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_levers_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac843301675394503b3b809d1a6430166">Incorrect. An antagonist works opposite of the prime mover.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad670a3fe406a467b95bfc1af4010d156">Correct. The agonist is the same thing as the prime mover.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="af6f896a24d7643ef81abb97d2d9dbb1e">Incorrect. A synergist helps the prime mover do its job.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="ade187afea3204e4eab0ad5fd27b5fe15">Incorrect. A fixator is a type of synergist, and a synergist helps the prime mover do its job.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q9_s" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ac63ed34adcd14cc0bac9533947fcadcb">You can pick up clues about the muscle itself or its action from understanding the complete name of the muscle. What information can you tell about the rectus femoris just from its name?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="b06ce1c0fc334f75bf59ddcd1a875c41" labels="false"><choice value="A">The location and the shape.</choice><choice value="B">The number of origins and the shape.</choice><choice value="C">The direction of fibers and location.</choice><choice value="D">The direction of fibers and shape.</choice></input><part id="q9_s_p1"><skillref idref="_u5_type_of_muscle_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="af89c252097a34eeba4a334f128ebb00c">Incorrect. Femoris does indicate the location on the femur bone but rectus indicates the direction of the fibers relative to the midline.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae7307e2f04134977a8f3c78477ccedcb">Incorrect. The number of origins and the shape are not indicated in this name.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="add919bc413df4d69a6ec1915a03aaa61">Correct. Rectus indicates the fibers run straight relative to the midline. Femoris indicates the location on the femur bone.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="aebd334800d074282a7d956f0979eacfa">Incorrect. Rectus does indicate the direction of the fibers relative to midline but femoris does not indicate shape.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice></page></assessment>
